@node usage "Usage"

	@{b}Usage@{ub}
	@{"Modes and syntax" link modes}
	@{"Setup a dir     " link dir}

	It might seem quite complicated to use backuper. @{"I" link me} know that, but the time spent in installing Backuper to a couple of buttons in your favourite filehandler will be gained in always having the functions in reach.
@endnode


@node modes

	@{b}Modes and syntax@{ub}

	Backuper has four modes:
		Scan
		Joinfree
		Joinlist
		Help

	@{b}Scan@{ub}
	Is used to read the contents of your disks. You should use it everytime a disk has changed or you want to add a new disk.
	@{b}Syntax@{ub}
	Backuper 'the dir where you ceep your backup files' scan 'disk to scan'
	Example:
	Backuper "work:backup/" scan df0:

	@{b}Joinfree@{ub}
	Joinfree creates a file named 'free'. 'free' is a list over all the scanned disks, and how much space there is left on each of them.
	@{b}Syntax@{ub}
	Backuper 'the dir where you ceep your backup files' joinfree
	Example:
	Backuper "work:backup/" joinfree

	@{b}Joinlist@{ub}
	Joinlist creates the files 'name', 'disk', 'date' and 'size'. These are lists over all files on the scanned disks, sorted in diffrent orders.
	@{b}Syntax@{ub}
	Backuper 'the dir where you ceep your backup files' joinlist
	Example:
	Backuper "work:backup/" joinlist

	@{b}Help@{ub}
	Help prints out the available modes.
	@{b}Syntax@{ub}
	Backuper 'the dir where you ceep your backup files' help
	Example:
	Backuper "work:backup/" help
@endnode


@node dir

	@{b}Setup a dir@{ub}

	Backuper wants a dir named 'disks' to collect it's own files in. Create this dir, and everything will work fine.

	Example:
	You want to store all your backup files in 'work:backup/', you should then create a dir in 'work:backup/' named 'disks'.
@endnode
